2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.024a2aa2-731f-49e2-82cc-af5866bd4bc2.prompt=HostName\: 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.0f3f0356-b151-4553-8fca-736ed6d13572.prompt=Password\: 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.361ddcae-467b-4c51-9b9c-aaeacd12bd56.prompt=HostName\: 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.5711771b-3941-4b95-8caa-764fa8ab1908.description=
Runs multiple SSH command by creating an ssh shell and checking output against regular expressions

Inputs\:
host - hostname or ip address
port - the port number for running the command. It overwrites the port given inside the host input -in a syntax like host\:port-, if this exists.
command - the commands to execute. This should be made up of 'send ' and 'expect ' statements separated be newlines.
username - username to connect as
password - password
privateKeyFile - private key to be used during ssh authentication.
timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete
newlineCharacters - The character sequence to send as the enter key being pressed after each 'send' statement in a send expect script is processed. Either '\r\n' '\n' '\r' or a comma delimited list of ASCII escape sequences.
characterDelay - the delay in milliseconds between sending characters of the SSH commands. 

Responses\:
success - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
visualized - the output of the command in XML format
STDOUT - the STDOUT of the command

2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.83b9ec07-1c98-4e9a-bb7e-1cf5546f4233.description=This operation runs Perl scripts from a file. Inputs\: scriptFile - The path to the script file. args - The arguments to be passed to the script. timeout - The time to wait for the command to complete (in milliseconds). Default value\: 90000 (90 seconds). Returns\: returnResult - The return code of the operation\: -1 for failure, 0 for success. Output String - The output of the Perl script. TimedOut - Returns if the operation was timed out. Valid values\: true, false Error String - The error returned by the operation. Responses\: success - The operation run successfully or the operation run without errors and a timeout occured. failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. For example\: if the script file was not found, invalid script. Notes\: 1. As a prerequisite, Perl must be installed on the machine (Studio/Central/RAS). 2. The operation returns the output of a "perl -W ". 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.942ac53c-3fe1-4fec-9d0b-368d1edf5c9d.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.aefd834f-bbde-4c2b-a8e1-638a4a7ad3f0.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.
2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.b670cb4f-c7b4-4b90-9508-01347d9c2d58.prompt=UserName\: 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.becb2429-9dbc-4907-9251-4f7a2e93f083.prompt=Password\: 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.c883c082-344d-4a7b-97a0-1b454e683e51.transition.description=Closed SSH Shell session 2058bb31-8434-4d0c-ad15-6cb65335adc4.ce3fb8e1-6d18-4543-8601-db63f9dc89eb.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
